coverType Data Set - Modelling

Brian Carter

24 March, 2015

Introduction¶

  • Build out typical workflow of a data mining project on the coverTye dataset
  • coveType column is the target (7 classes, class imbalance)
  • Use Python sklean library
  • Make use of Pipelining for feature transformation
  • Plot results using Matplotlib normalised confusion matrix (equal weight to each class, regardless of size)
  • Select approrpiate score for comparing models F1_macro
  • GridSearch for the optimal set of parameters on best model
  • Evaluate on the Test Data
  • Training on 10% of data






Data Loading¶

  • Load covertype15.csv without columns in binary form (15 columns)
  • Convert categoricals to dtype pd.Categoricals(). (N.B. this is not valid dtype for storing)

#Libraries required
import platform
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd
  
#Currently pd.Categorical is not a valid dtype so they come in as objects. Need to convert.
colTypes = {'Elevation':np.float64,'Aspect':np.float64,'Slope':np.float64,'HD.Hydro':np.float64,
            'VD.Hyrdro': np.float64,'HD.Road': np.float64, 'HS.9am':np.float64,'HS.noon':np.float64,
            'HS.3pm':np.float64,'wildernessArea':pd.Categorical,'soilType':pd.Categorical,
            'climaticZone':pd.Categorical,'geologicZone':pd.Categorical,'coverType':pd.Categorical}

#Read in the data without binary encoding, 15 original columns 
coverData = pd.read_csv("../Data/covtype15.csv",dtype=colTypes )
print ("CoverData Memory usage %s MB" % round(coverData.memory_usage().sum()/1000000,1))

#Set up values for converting to categorical 
CATEGORYCOLUMNS = ['wildernessArea','soilType','climaticZone','geologicZone']

#Loop through and covert to category
for column in CATEGORYCOLUMNS:
    factors = list(coverData[column].unique())
    coverData[column] = pd.Categorical(coverData[column], categories=factors)
    
print ("CoverData Memory usage %s MB\n" % round(coverData.memory_usage().sum()/1000000,1))

Create Input Features and Target¶

  • Use generic X for feature input space
  • use generic y for target variable - encode the values as numeric

10% of the data will be used for the training data. 5 Fold Cross Validation is used to create better approximation of the true test set errors .

Using sklearn.cross_validation negates the need for a sepearte validation set.

In [3]:
import sklearn.cross_validation as cv
from sklearn import preprocessing

#store for Later use
targetLabels=['1.Spruce','2.Lodge','3.Ponder','4.Cotton','5.Aspen','6.Douglas','7.Krymmholz']


#Create generic X input feature space
X = coverData.drop('coverType', axis=1)

#Get the list of feature names. Will use later for extracting feature importances. 
inputFeatures = list(pd.get_dummies(X).columns)

#Using LabelEncoder to encode the target variable coverType
le = preprocessing.LabelEncoder()
le.fit(coverData['coverType'])
y=le.transform(coverData['coverType'])

#Create splits for the training and test sets. Set random state for reproducibility
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = cv.train_test_split(X,y,test_size=0.9,random_state=79)







Five Baseline Models¶

  • Multionominal Naive Bayes
  • Decision Tree - Depth 10
  • Stochastic Gradient Descent - log loss - Logistic Regression

Stoachastic Gradient Descent is gradient descent bit only use a sample of the data for tuning each parameter. Converges quicker than gradient descent. Using log as the loss function makes it a logistic regression. Similar hinge(maximum-margin) loss makes it approximate an SVM.

  • Stochastic Gradient Descent - hinge loss - SVM
  • Random Forest - 100 Trees - Use 1/3 features at each split choice.

Question: should max_features be increased when using dummy encoded variables ???

Model Pipeline¶

  • The purpose of the pipeline is to assemble several steps together in chain

  • Similar functionality in Spark ML API
  • The Spark ML API pipeline concept is mostly inspired by the scikit-learn project. http://spark.apache.org/docs/latest/ml-guide.html

#setup models
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler, MinMaxScaler,normalize,Normalizer

from sklearn.naive_bayes import MultinomialNB
from sklearn import tree
from sklearn.linear_model import SGDClassifier
from sklearn.ensemble import RandomForestClassifier
#from sklearn.svm import SVC
#from sklearn import neighbors

from sklearn.pipeline import make_pipeline

CLASSIFIERS1 = [make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), MinMaxScaler(feature_range=(0,1)),
                             MultinomialNB()),
               
               make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini',max_depth=10,min_samples_split=20)),
               
               make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             SGDClassifier(loss="log",n_jobs=4)),
               
               make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler()
                             ,SGDClassifier(loss="hinge",n_jobs=4)),
               
               make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             RandomForestClassifier(n_estimators=100, max_features=22,max_depth=10,min_samples_split=20,
                                                    random_state=0,n_jobs=4))
              ]

MODELNAMES1 =  ['NaiveBayes','DecisionTree','SGD-Log','SGD-Hinge','RandomForest']

Train Data Fit¶

  • Loop through each of the classifiers and fit data
  • Collect train data model evaluation metrics (time to fit, precision_macro, recall_macro, f1_macro, confusion matrix) (time: some estimators using 4 cores: SGD, RandomForest)
  • Use sklearn.metrics.classification report.
In [35]:
#run models
from sklearn.metrics import confusion_matrix,classification_report,f1_score
import time


#Lists to hold results
RESULTS1 = []
CONFUSIONMATRIX1 = []
CLASSIFICATIONREPORT1 = []
scores = ['precision_macro','recall_macro','f1_macro']

for pipe,model_name in zip(CLASSIFIERS1, MODELNAMES1):
    
    #Fit the model
    start = time.time()
    pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)
    totalMilliSec = round((time.time()-start)*1000,1)
    
    #Cross validation 5 k-fold get accurate estatimate of the training scores. 
    train_scores = {score: cv.cross_val_score(pipe,X_train,y_train,cv=5,scoring=score) for score in scores}
    
    #Save the train scores in RESULTS
    results_dict = {'model': model_name ,
                    'timeMS' : totalMilliSec,
                    'precision' : round(train_scores['precision_macro'].mean(),3),
                    'recall' :    round(train_scores['recall_macro'].mean(),3),
                    'f1-score' :  round(train_scores['f1_macro'].mean(),3)
                   }
    
    RESULTS1.append(dict(results_dict))
    
    
    #Create Train prediction for calculating Decision Report and Confusion Matrix. 
    y_train_pred = pipe.predict(X_train)
        
    # Create measures based on confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred)
    CONFUSIONMATRIX1.append(cm)
    
    classreport = classification_report(y_train, y_train_pred,target_names=targetLabels)
    CLASSIFICATIONREPORT1.append(classreport)

Model Evaluation¶

For each of the models generate a classificaiton report with;

  • recall - a measure of the classifiers completness. *((E.g.How many of the TRUE 1.Spruce are found. In first example Recall = 16474/(21247)) = 0.78
  • precision - a measure of the classifiers exactness. *(E.g.How many of the rows predict 1.Spruce are TRUE 1.Spruce. In first example Precision = 16474/(16474+3864+0+0+13+1+434) = 0.79
  • f1_score - balanced average of both = (precision*recall)/(precision+recall)
  • Using the macro average over all classes - results in each classes being given equal importance. A micro average would take into account class size.
  • A normalized confusion matrix on the train set is used to plot on a heatmap. Normalizing gives each class equal weight. The darker the colour is better. Looking for a dark diagonal.

Not used

  • accuracy - doesn't make sense with class imbalance. Will favour majority classes. Is calculated for comprhension.

  • cohen kappa

    • classification accuracy normalized by the imbalance of the clsses in the data. Not an agreed measure for classification problems. The kappa score (see docstring) is a number between -1 and 1. Scores above .8 are generally considered good agreement; zero or lower means no agreement (practically random labels).

Decision Trees¶

The DecisionTree had max depth of 10 nodes and returned the best F1 score. This tree is re-creatd and other variants of Decision Trees are created;

  • Decision Tree - Max Depth 5
  • Decision Tree - Max Depth 10 (previous Tree)
  • Decision Tree - using entropy as the criteria for splitting.

Gini will tend to find the largest class, and entropy tends to find groups of classes that make up ~50% of the data((http://paginas.fe.up.pt/~ec/files_1011/week%2008%20-%20Decision%20Trees.pdf))

  • Weighted Tree - use the class distribution to inversely weight trees so smaller classes have greater weight.
  • Full Tree - no limit on depth, stopping criteria is 20 rows per leaf

Full Tree will overfit the data. Sklearn does not provide method for pruning at present

In [29]:
#Determine the weights by inverse proportion
inverseFreq  = 1./ np.bincount(y_train)
coverTypeWeights = inverseFreq / np.mean(inverseFreq)
#DecisionTreeClassifier requires dictionary of weights
coverTypeWeights = dict(zip(range(7), coverTypeWeights))

CLASSIFIERS2 = [make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini',max_depth=5,min_samples_split=20)),
        
                make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini',max_depth=10,min_samples_split=20)),
                
                make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy',max_depth=10,min_samples_split=20)),
                
                make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini',max_depth=10,min_samples_split=20,
                                                         class_weight=coverTypeWeights)),
                
                make_pipeline(CategoricalTransformer(), StandardScaler(),
                             tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='gini',max_depth=None,min_samples_split=20))]              

MODELNAMES2 =  ['Depth5 Tree','Original Tree','Entropy Tree','Weighted Tree','FullTree']
In [30]:
#Lists to hold results
RESULTS2 = []
CONFUSIONMATRIX2 = []
CLASSIFICATIONREPORT2 = []

scores = ['precision_macro','recall_macro','f1_macro']

for pipe,model_name in zip(CLASSIFIERS2, MODELNAMES2):
    
    #Fit the model
    start = time.time()
    pipe.fit(X_train, y_train)
    totalMilliSec = round((time.time()-start)*1000,1) #milliseconds
    
    #Cross validation 5 k-fold get accurate estatimate of the training scores. 
    train_scores = {score: cv.cross_val_score(pipe,X_train,y_train,cv=5,scoring=score) for score in scores}
    
    #Extract the feature importance
    featureImport=(pipe.steps[2][1].feature_importances_).round(3)
    topFeautureIndex = featureImport.argsort()[5:][::-1]

    #Save the train scores in RESULTS
    results_dict = {'model': model_name ,
                    'timeMS' : totalMilliSec,
                    'precision' : round(train_scores['precision_macro'].mean(),3),
                    'recall' :    round(train_scores['recall_macro'].mean(),3),
                    'f1-score' :  round(train_scores['f1_macro'].mean(),3),
                    'top feature' :   [inputFeatures[i] for i in topFeautureIndex],
                    'feature score' :    [featureImport[i] for i in topFeautureIndex]
                   }
    
    RESULTS2.append(dict(results_dict))
    
    
    #Create Train prediction for calculating Decision Report and Confusion Matrix. 
    y_train_pred = pipe.predict(X_train)
        
    # Create measures based on confusion matrix
    cm = confusion_matrix(y_train, y_train_pred)
    CONFUSIONMATRIX2.append(cm)
    
    classreport = classification_report(y_train, y_train_pred,target_names=targetLabels)
    CLASSIFICATIONREPORT2.append(classreport)

Entropy, One-vs-Rest, Ensemble¶

Building on the increase in the F1-score using Entrop splitting criteria, return to a previous ensemble model RandomForest and alter the splitting criterion.

  • Decision Tree Entropy
  • Random Forest with DT Entropy

Introduce a OneVsRestClassifier. This increases the complexity as in effect 7 models are trained, one for each class.

  • One-vs-Rest DT
  • One-vs-Rest RF

Introduce AdaBoost model. Ensemble method at each iteration focus on missclassified rows. Should force algorithm to focus on smaller classes. (NB AdaBoost not easily parallisable - takes long time to fit).

  • AdaBoost

Grid Search¶

Search Parameters¶

In the previous iteration the best F1-Score occured with a OneVsRest implementation of a DecisionTreeClassifier.

Use this model and iterate of all possible comibinations of four DecisionTreeClassifier parameters.

  • Maximum Depth - how many levels the tree contains
  • Minimum Splits - cutoff, if a leaf node is below threshold no further splitting occurs.
  • Maximum Features to Consider - at each split take all the reamining features in account or a sample
  • Class Weights
    • Utilising OneVsRest alter the weights so that each class has equal importance. Will favour smaller classes.

Intuition - The maximum depth tree will be favoured with the smallest number of rows per leaf. There will be tradeoff between these two values.

GridSearch - has many iterations. In order to minimise computation time, transform the training data first rather than for each iteration. Execute it in parallel with n_jobs parameter.

Scoring - Scoring will be set to f1-macro.

In [44]:
from sklearn.grid_search import GridSearchCV

#parameters to search
max_depthS = [10,20,30]
min_samples_splitS = [10,20,30]
max_featuresS = [0.5,'sqrt','log2',None]
class_weightS = [None,{0:0.5,1:0.5}]

#Need to include estimator__ when model is inside OnveVsRestClassifier

parameterGrid = {'estimator__max_depth' : max_depthS, 'estimator__min_samples_split' : min_samples_splitS, 
                  'estimator__max_features': max_featuresS,'estimator__class_weight' : class_weightS }

print (parameterGrid)

#Create the Grid Search, verbose indicates how details message are printed. Set to 1. Increase the number of cores to six.
grid_search = GridSearchCV(OneVsRestClassifier(tree.DecisionTreeClassifier(criterion='entropy')),
                                               parameterGrid, verbose=1,cv=5,n_jobs=6,scoring='f1_macro')

#Calculate the transformed Training Data. 
X_trainTransformed =  StandardScaler().fit_transform(pd.get_dummies(X_train))

#Set up model

Conclusions¶

  • Overall improvement in the F1_score from baseline of 0.659 with default sklearn.tree.DecisionTreeClassifier to 0.748 with optimal set of parameters.
  • The training data does not appear to overfit when examing the F1_macro score. However there is a significant drop off when examining the overall accuracy from 0.944 to 0.848.
  • Requires more extensive cross validation

Further Work

  • Improvement may be obtained by creating a pareto optimisation fuction with accuracy and f1_macro score for the grid search*
  • More data preperation - outlier analysis
  • No feature subsetting - feature selection methods implmeneted.

convert to pd.Categorical¶

In [15]:
#Function to convert column in data frame with dtype = Categorical to a binary represenation
#http://tomaugspurger.github.io/categorical-pipelines.html

""" 
    Parameters
    ----------
    X : Dataframe 
    
    Methods
    ----------
    fit : determine columns for conversion(was missing return in docs)
    transfom: apply conversion
    inverse_transform: return to original - not tested or used here
"""




from itertools import chain
from sklearn.pipeline import TransformerMixin

class CategoricalTransformer(TransformerMixin):

    def fit(self, X, y=None, *args, **kwargs):
        self.columns_ = X.columns
        self.cat_columns_ = X.select_dtypes(include=['category']).columns
        self.non_cat_columns_ = X.columns.drop(self.cat_columns_)

        self.cat_map_ = {col: X[col].cat.categories
                         for col in self.cat_columns_}
        self.ordered_ = {col: X[col].cat.ordered
                         for col in self.cat_columns_}

        self.dummy_columns_ = {col: ["_".join([col, v])
                                     for v in self.cat_map_[col]]
                               for col in self.cat_columns_}
        self.transformed_columns_ = pd.Index(
            self.non_cat_columns_.tolist() +
            list(chain.from_iterable(self.dummy_columns_[k]
                                     for k in self.cat_columns_))
        )
        
        return self

    def transform(self, X, y=None, *args, **kwargs):
        return (pd.get_dummies(X)
                  .reindex(columns=self.transformed_columns_)
                  .fillna(0))

    def inverse_transform(self, X):
        X = np.asarray(X)
        series = []
        non_cat_cols = (self.transformed_columns_
                            .get_indexer(self.non_cat_columns_))
        non_cat = pd.DataFrame(X[:, non_cat_cols],
                               columns=self.non_cat_columns_)
        for col, cat_cols in self.dummy_columns_.items():
            locs = self.transformed_columns_.get_indexer(cat_cols)
            codes = X[:, locs].argmax(1)
            cats = pd.Categorical.from_codes(codes, self.cat_map_[col],
                                             ordered=self.ordered_[col])
            series.append(pd.Series(cats, name=col))
        # concats sorts, we want the original order
        df = (pd.concat([non_cat] + series, axis=1)
                .reindex(columns=self.columns_))
        return df

self = CategoricalTransformer()  # for testing later

#Function to plot 5 confusion matrices.
import matplotlib
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
%matplotlib inline

""" 
    Parameters
    ----------
    CM : list of confusion matrices as returned from sklearn.metrics.onfusion_matrix
    MN : list of model names 
    cmap : colour palette from matplotlib - set to plt.cm.Blues    
"""

def multiConfusion(CM,MN,cmap=plt.cm.Blues):
    numberPlots = len(CM)
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,numberPlots, figsize=(18,4), facecolor='w', edgecolor='k')
    fig.suptitle("Confusion Matrices \n Normalized by Class Size", fontsize=14,fontweight='bold') 
    
    axs = axs.ravel()
    
    for c,m,i in zip(CM,MN,range(len(MN))) :
        cm_normalized = c.astype('float') / c.sum(axis=1)[:, np.newaxis]
        axs[i].imshow(cm_normalized, interpolation='nearest', cmap=cmap)
        axs[i].set_title(m)
        tick_marks = np.arange(len(targetLabels)+1)
        axs[i].set_xticklabels(tick_marks, rotation=90)
        axs[i].set_yticklabels(tick_marks)
        axs[i].set_ylabel('True label')
        axs[i].set_xlabel('Predicted label')

Extract Decision Tree Rules¶

In [17]:
#http://planspace.org/20151129-see_sklearn_trees_with_d3/
def rules(clf, features, labels, node_index=0):
    
    """Structure of rules in a fit decision tree classifier

    Parameters
    ----------
    clf : DecisionTreeClassifier
        A tree that has already been fit.

    features, labels : lists of str
        The names of the features and labels, respectively.

    """
    node = {}
    if clf.tree_.children_left[node_index] == -1:  # indicates leaf
        count_labels = zip(clf.tree_.value[node_index, 0], labels)
        node['name'] = ', '.join(('{} of {}'.format(int(count), label)
                                  for count, label in count_labels))
    else:
        feature = features[clf.tree_.feature[node_index]]
        threshold = clf.tree_.threshold[node_index]
        node['name'] = '{} > {}'.format(feature, threshold)
        left_index = clf.tree_.children_left[node_index]
        right_index = clf.tree_.children_right[node_index]
        node['children'] = [rules(clf, features, labels, right_index),
                            rules(clf, features, labels, left_index)]
    return node

#Create a copy of the training dataset
clusterDF=X_train.ix[:,0:17]
clusterDF['y_train']=y_train

from sklearn.decomposition import PCA

#scale Data to standard Normal
scaledData = preprocessing.StandardScaler().fit_transform(clusterDF.ix[:,0:10])
scaledData = preprocessing.normalize(clusterDF.ix[:,0:10])

for i in range(1,3):
    pca = PCA(n_components=i)
    pca.fit(scaledData)
    variance=sum(pca.explained_variance_ratio_)
    print('Explained variance ratio of the %s components with normalized data: %s'% (i,variance))
    
    #Save first two pca for plot
    if i == 2:
        saveVariance = variance        
        numericPCA = pca.transform(scaledData)
        clusterDF['PC1']=numericPCA[:,0]
        clusterDF['PC2']=numericPCA[:,1]

from matplotlib.colors import rgb2hex
colormap = plt.get_cmap('hsv') 

#@colormap is set
#@breaks varied depending on number of levels. E.g. Warning: yes|no has two levels.

def colors_at_breaks(colormap, breaks):
    return [rgb2hex(colormap(x)) for x in breaks]
